# Lambda Expressions and Functional Interfaces in Java

## Introduction
Lambda expressions are a powerful feature in Java that enable functional programming paradigms, allowing developers to write more concise and expressive code.

## Concept Overview
Lambda expressions provide a way to represent anonymous functions as first-class language constructs. They are particularly useful with functional interfaces - interfaces with a single abstract method.

## Syntax
```java
// Basic lambda syntax
(parameters) -> { method body }

// Single parameter lambda
parameter -> expression

// Multiple parameters
(param1, param2) -> { 
    // Multiple statements 
    return result;
}
```

## Functional Interface Examples
```java
// Traditional approach
Runnable runner = new Runnable() {
    public void run() {
        System.out.println("Traditional implementation");
    }
};

// Lambda equivalent
Runnable lambdaRunner = () -> System.out.println("Lambda implementation");
```

## Key Points
- Lambdas simplify code by reducing boilerplate
- They work seamlessly with functional interfaces
- Supports type inference
- Can capture variables from enclosing scope

## C# Comparison
- Similar to C# lambda expressions
- Java lambdas are more restrictive compared to C# delegates
- Both languages support functional programming concepts

## Common Mistakes
- Overusing lambdas for complex logic
- Forgetting type inference rules
- Misunderstanding variable capture rules

## Practice Exercises
```java
// Exercise: Create a lambda to filter even numbers
List<Integer> numbers = Arrays.asList(1, 2, 3, 4, 5);
List<Integer> evenNumbers = numbers.stream()
    .filter(n -> n % 2 == 0)
    .collect(Collectors.toList());
```

## Advanced Usage
```java
// Functional interface with multiple methods
@FunctionalInterface
interface Calculator {
    int compute(int a, int b);

    // Default method allowed
    default void log() {
        System.out.println("Calculation performed");
    }
}
```

